 lifestyle factors.", "monitoring": ["Retest total and free T in 6-12 months", "Monitor symptoms of low T", "Track energy and libido"], "recommended": false, "naturalAlternatives": ["Quality sleep (7-9 hours)", "Resistance training 3-4x weekly", "Stress management", "Maintain healthy body fat (10-20%)", "Zinc and Vitamin D optimization", "Limit alcohol consumption"]}, "testosteroneStatus": "good"}	{"hba1c": 5.2, "notes": "Excellent metabolic health. Fasting glucose of 92 mg/dL is optimal (under 100). HbA1c of 5.2% indicates excellent long-term glucose control. Insulin at 6.8 uIU/mL shows no hyperinsulinemia. HOMA-IR of 1.5 indicates good insulin sensitivity. Maintain through regular exercise, balanced nutrition with adequate protein, and avoiding processed carbohydrates.", "homaIr": 1.5, "glucose": 92, "insulin": 6.8}	{"crp": 0.8, "notes": "Inflammation markers are well-controlled. CRP at 0.8 mg/L (optimal <1.0) indicates low systemic inflammation. Homocysteine at 8.2 umol/L is healthy (optimal <10). Ferritin at 95 ng/mL is balanced - enough iron stores without excess oxidative potential. Continue anti-inflammatory practices: omega-3 fatty acids, colorful vegetables, quality sleep, stress management.", "status": "good", "ferritin": 95, "homocysteine": 8.2}	[{"time": "6:00 AM", "action": "Wake + Morning Light", "details": "Get 10-15 minutes of direct sunlight exposure within the first hour of waking. This sets your circadian rhythm, triggers cortisol awakening response, and programs better melatonin release 14-16 hours later. Even on cloudy days, outdoor light is 10-50x brighter than indoor lighting.", "priority": "high"}, {"time": "6:15 AM", "action": "Hydration Protocol", "details": "Drink 16-20oz water with a pinch of sea salt (sodium) or electrolyte mix. After 7-8 hours without water, you wake dehydrated. Proper hydration improves cognitive function, energy, and nutrient transport. Add lemon if desired for digestion support.", "priority": "high"}, {"time": "6:25 AM", "action": "Cold Exposure", "details": "End your shower with 1-3 minutes of cold water (as cold as tolerable). This increases norepinephrine by 200-300%, improving mood and alertness for hours. Cold exposure also activates brown fat, improves recovery, and builds mental resilience. Start with 30 seconds and gradually increase.", "priority": "medium"}, {"time": "6:35 AM", "action": "Movement/Mobility", "details": "10-15 minute mobility routine focusing on hips, thoracic spine, and shoulders. This activates the nervous system, improves joint health, and prepares your body for the day. Include cat-cow stretches, hip circles, and shoulder rotations.", "priority": "medium"}, {"time": "6:50 AM", "action": "Breathwork", "details": "5-10 minutes of box breathing (4 seconds inhale, 4 hold, 4 exhale, 4 hold) or similar practice. This activates parasympathetic nervous system, reduces cortisol, and improves focus. Sets calm, intentional tone for the day.", "priority": "medium"}]	[{"time": "7:00 PM", "action": "Dim Lights & Block Blue Light", "details": "Switch to warm lighting and wear blue light blocking glasses. Blue light after sunset suppresses melatonin production by up to 50%. This single habit can dramatically improve sleep quality. Use red/amber lights in bedroom.", "priority": "high"}, {"time": "8:00 PM", "action": "Digital Sunset", "details": "Stop work emails and stimulating content. Transition to relaxing activities: reading (paper book preferred), gentle stretching, conversation, or meditation. Cortisol should naturally decline in evening - don't spike it with stressful content.", "priority": "high"}, {"time": "8:30 PM", "action": "Evening Supplements", "details": "Take magnesium glycinate 300-400mg. Magnesium supports GABA activity for calm, aids muscle relaxation, and improves sleep architecture. Best taken 1-2 hours before bed. Add zinc 15-30mg if levels are suboptimal.", "priority": "high"}, {"time": "9:00 PM", "action": "Cool Down Environment", "details": "Set bedroom temperature to 65-68°F (18-20°C). Your core body temperature must drop 2-3 degrees for sleep onset and to stay asleep. This is physiologically non-negotiable. Consider a cooling mattress pad if overheating is an issue.", "priority": "high"}, {"time": "9:30-10:00 PM", "action": "Sleep", "details": "Aim for consistent bedtime within a 30-minute window, even on weekends. Adults need 7-9 hours. Sleep is when growth hormone peaks (especially first 90 min), memories consolidate, the glymphatic system clears brain toxins, and tissue repairs occur. It's not optional for optimization.", "priority": "high"}]	[{"name": "Vitamin D3", "notes": "Target blood level of 40-60 ng/mL. Most people do well with 1000-2000 IU. Only increase if blood levels remain low despite supplementation.", "dosage": "1000-2000 IU daily (NOT 5000 IU unless severely deficient)", "timing": "Morning with fat-containing meal", "purpose": "Optimize vitamin D for immune function, bone health, and hormone production", "mechanism": "Fat-soluble hormone precursor that regulates 200+ genes including immune modulation, calcium homeostasis, and testosterone synthesis. Vitamin D receptors exist in nearly every tissue.", "synergies": ["Vitamin K2", "Magnesium", "Omega-3"], "precautions": "Retest levels after 3 months. 5000 IU is excessive for most people and can lead to hypercalcemia long-term. Take with K2 to direct calcium to bones, not arteries.", "evidenceLevel": "strong", "expectedBenefits": "Improved immune function, better mood, optimized hormone levels, reduced inflammation, stronger bones"}, {"name": "Omega-3 (EPA/DHA)", "notes": "Aim for higher EPA for inflammation, higher DHA for brain. Many people are deficient due to low fish intake.", "dosage": "2-3g combined EPA/DHA daily", "timing": "With meals containing fat for absorption", "purpose": "Reduce inflammation, support brain health, cardiovascular protection", "mechanism": "EPA and DHA are incorporated into cell membranes, improving fluidity. They compete with omega-6 for enzymatic conversion, reducing pro-inflammatory eicosanoids. Critical for brain structure and function.", "synergies": ["Vitamin D", "Curcumin", "Astaxanthin"], "precautions": "Choose quality fish oil or algae-based (for vegans) to avoid heavy metals. May thin blood slightly - mention to doctor before surgery.", "evidenceLevel": "strong", "expectedBenefits": "Reduced inflammation (lower CRP), improved mood, better cognitive function, cardiovascular protection, reduced joint pain"}, {"name": "Magnesium Glycinate", "notes": "Most people are deficient due to depleted soils and low intake. Critical mineral for optimization.", "dosage": "300-400mg elemental magnesium before bed", "timing": "1-2 hours before sleep", "purpose": "Sleep quality, muscle relaxation, stress reduction, 300+ enzymatic reactions", "mechanism": "Magnesium is cofactor in 300+ enzymatic reactions. Glycinate form crosses blood-brain barrier, supports GABA activity (calming neurotransmitter), relaxes muscles, and improves sleep architecture.", "synergies": ["Vitamin D", "B6", "Zinc"], "precautions": "Glycinate is well-tolerated. Oxide form is poorly absorbed and causes GI issues. Threonate is good for cognitive focus.", "evidenceLevel": "strong", "expectedBenefits": "Better sleep quality, reduced muscle tension, improved stress response, better exercise recovery, regular bowel movements"}, {"name": "Creatine Monohydrate", "notes": "One of the most studied and effective supplements. Benefits both athletes and non-athletes for brain health.", "dosage": "5g daily", "timing": "Anytime - with food or post-workout", "purpose": "Strength, power, cognitive function, cellular energy", "mechanism": "Creatine is stored as phosphocreatine in muscles and brain, rapidly regenerating ATP during high-intensity activity. Also has cognitive benefits through brain energy metabolism.", "synergies": ["Beta-Alanine", "HMB", "Protein"], "precautions": "Stay well hydrated. No loading phase necessary - 5g daily reaches saturation in 3-4 weeks. Monohydrate is the most studied form.", "evidenceLevel": "strong", "expectedBenefits": "Increased strength and power output, faster recovery between sets, improved cognitive performance, potential neuroprotective effects"}]	[{"day": "Monday", "type": "Upper Body Push", "duration": "45-50 min", "exercises": ["Bench Press 4x6-8 RPE 7-8", "Overhead Press 3x8-10", "Dips 3x10-12", "Lateral Raises 4x12-15", "Tricep Pushdowns 3x12-15"], "intensity": "High"}, {"day": "Tuesday", "type": "Lower Body", "duration": "50 min", "exercises": ["Squats 4x6-8 RPE 7-8", "Romanian Deadlifts 4x8-10", "Bulgarian Split Squats 3x10 each", "Leg Curls 3x12", "Calf Raises 4x15"], "intensity": "High"}, {"day": "Wednesday", "type": "Active Recovery", "duration": "45-60 min", "exercises": ["30-min Zone 2 walk or light cardio", "15-min full body mobility routine", "10-min foam rolling"], "intensity": "Low - conversational pace"}, {"day": "Thursday", "type": "Upper Body Pull", "duration": "45 min", "exercises": ["Pull-ups or Lat Pulldowns 4x6-10", "Barbell or Dumbbell Rows 4x8-10", "Face Pulls 3x15-20", "Bicep Curls 3x12", "Rear Delt Flies 3x15"], "intensity": "High"}, {"day": "Friday", "type": "Lower Body + Deadlift Focus", "duration": "50 min", "exercises": ["Deadlifts 4x5 RPE 7-8", "Leg Press 3x10-12", "Walking Lunges 3x10 each", "Leg Extensions 3x12", "Core Work 10 min"], "intensity": "High"}, {"day": "Saturday", "type": "Zone 2 Cardio + Flexibility", "duration": "60-75 min", "exercises": ["45-60 min steady cardio at conversational pace (cycling, jogging, rowing)", "15-20 min stretching or yoga"], "intensity": "Low - Heart rate 60-70% max"}, {"day": "Sunday", "type": "Complete Rest or Light Activity", "duration": "Optional", "exercises": ["Optional: gentle walk, yoga, family activities", "Focus on recovery, meal prep, and sleep"], "intensity": "Very Low"}]	[{"level": "low", "category": "Vitamin D Optimization", "description": "Ensure vitamin D 